As mentioned above, the radius of QDs can be managed in order to produce optical gain output at specific frequencies; i.e., a QD with a specific radius R0 will produce gain output at its corresponding energy E0. Thus, one can obtain broadband optical gain spectrum by simultaneously using several QDs with various values of R0. This broadening behavior underlies our superimposed model in which QDs are engineered so that their broadening profiles will lead to ultra-broadband optical gain spectrum. As one can see in Fig. 2, the resonant energy for each group at which gain output reaches its peak value is:1EMi=ED1+D2+…+Di+i\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
